<h1> This is the xmountains home page</h1>

<p>
Xmountains is a fractal terrain generator written by
<a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20120524103707/http://www.epcc.ed.ac.uk/%7Espb/bio.html"> Stephen Booth </a>
There is also a
<a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20120524103707/http://www2.epcc.ed.ac.uk/%7Espb/javamountains/javamountains.html">
Java version of this code.</a>


</p>
<p>
If you find any bugs send me an <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20120524103707/http://www2.epcc.ed.ac.uk/%7Espb/xmountains/contact-form.html">Email</a>
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20120524103707/http://www2.epcc.ed.ac.uk/%7Espb/xmountains/about_xmountains.html">
There is a page describing how the program works.</a>
</p>
<p>
You can also look at the <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20120524103707/http://www2.epcc.ed.ac.uk/%7Espb/xmountains/source.html">source code</a> on the web.
</p>

<h2> The current release is 2.9 </h2>

<ul>
<li> <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20120524103707/http://www2.epcc.ed.ac.uk/%7Espb/xmountains/xmountains_2.9.tar.gz"> xmountains_2.9.tar.gz </a> </li>
</ul>

